IE360: Statistical Forecasting and Time Series, Spring 2020 Term Project¶

Group 12: Sadullah Gültekin, Yusuf Başpınar, Serhat Yılmaz, Bahadır Hocamoğlu¶

July 5, 2020¶

Introduction¶

In this project, we are given a time series data collected from Trendyol e-commerce platform. There is data for approximately 3,5 months for different products. The products are given on a daily basis. We are asked to make a prediction for next days sold counts for each given product as accurately as possible. In the data there are eleven attributes. They are;

  • product ID (unique id for each product)
  • price of the product
  • date
  • sale count
  • favored count (number of times, the product is favored by a customer)
  • basket count (number of times, the product is added to the basket by a customer)
  • category sold (number of times the product with the same category is sold)
  • brand sold (number of times the product with the same brand is sold)
  • category visit (number of visits done to the same category)
  • trendyol visit (number of visits done to Trendyol)

Approach¶

Initially, we made a thorough analysis of the data. In the data there are various attributes related with a single product for each day. The names of the attribute is given in the introduction section. We are asked to predict the sold count for the next day, using previous sold count information and other related variables. First, we iterated all products and looked for the correlations between different attributes. To see the correlation, we tried to find which features are the most correlated ones. To be able to detect it, we created a heatmap for each product (these heatmaps can be seen in the output section of the code). We observed that the basket count and visit count are the most correlated features for most of the products. Favored count is also important for some products, however, when it is compared with other two attribute, we decided to ignore it.

At the starting parts of the project, we didnt use any of these attributes. Simply, we looked to the sold count and made a prediction using tree different model using statsmodel library of python. These models were Autoregressive model, Moving Average Model and ARIMA model. We were simply performing a procedure to decide which model works better for predicting the last 15 days. The procedure is as follows: we used all data until 15 days ago to train a model, and use it to make a prediction for 14 days ago. Then we did the same process for 14 days, 13 days, etc. After running 15 different prediction iterations, we took the average value of the error done at each prediction. In the calculation of error, we used MSE(Minimum Squared Error). We run the procedure described above for 3 models and selected the one with the lowest error to make a prediction for the next day.

When the last submission got closer, we found that there is a auto arima function in the python, and using this function we can utilize more models using a simple script. So we trained different models for different products using this model. One advantage of this model was using all variables to make a prediction. Using this model, we became able to calculate the values of differencings. In this multivariate model, we used endogenous variables and exogenous variables. Endogenous variable was the sold count, because we are trying to predict the value of this attribute. Exogenous variables were visit count and basket count, because we are making use of these variables to predict endogenous variables. However, we needed to have the values of exogenous variables corresponding to the next day. So, we made a prediction for these variables, and used the predictions as an input for sold count prediction model. Using this methodology, we made an average success. Reported the code, plot graphs and heatmaps in the code below.

To conclude, we made predictions for each product using different approaches. When we observed the data, there were unexpected and non-understandable points. The reason may be the pandemic, for it changed the habits of people. These kinds of unexpected data points may decrease after a couple of months and we can make smoother predictions. As our approach, we used a moving average model, ARIMA model and Auto Regressive model. As the output, we used the one with the lowest MSE. When we look at the scores we got from the predictions, we ranked 8 among 24 groups in total after final submission. Except for 2 days, we were able to make a prediction.

features = [
    'sold_count',
    'visit_count',
    'favored_count',
    'basket_count',
    'category_sold',
    'category_brand_sold',
    'category_visits',
    'ty_visits',]

for product in data_grouped_by_id:
    product_id = product[0]
    product_data = product[1][features]
    print(f'Product {product_id}:')
    print(product_data.describe())

    corr = np.corrcoef(product_data.T.replace(np.nan, 0))
    plt.figure(figsize = (18,8))
    heatmap = sns.heatmap(
        corr,
        cmap=choice(['Greys', 'Purples', 'Blues', 'Greens', 'Oranges', 'Reds',
            'YlOrBr', 'YlOrRd', 'OrRd', 'PuRd', 'RdPu', 'BuPu',
            'GnBu', 'PuBu', 'YlGnBu', 'PuBuGn', 'BuGn', 'YlGn']),
        annot=True,
        xticklabels=features,
        yticklabels=features)
    plt.show()

    sold_count = product_data['sold_count'].to_numpy()
    visit_count = product_data['visit_count'].to_numpy()
    basket_count = product_data['basket_count'].to_numpy()

    sold_count = (sold_count - np.min(sold_count)) / (np.max(sold_count) - np.min(sold_count))
    visit_count = (visit_count - np.min(visit_count)) / (np.max(visit_count) - np.min(visit_count))
    basket_count = (basket_count - np.min(basket_count)) / (np.max(basket_count) - np.min(basket_count))

    plt.figure(figsize = (18,8))
    plt.title('Sold count / Visit count')
    plt.plot(range(len(sold_count)), sold_count)
    plt.plot(range(len(visit_count)), visit_count)
    plt.show()

    plt.figure(figsize = (18,8))
    plt.title('Sold count / Basket count')
    plt.plot(range(len(sold_count)), sold_count)
    plt.plot(range(len(basket_count)), visit_count)
    plt.show()

    print()

def arimamodel(timeseriesarray, exogenous=None, trace=False):
    return pmd.auto_arima(  # equivalent to auto.arima in R
        timeseriesarray,
        exogenous=exogenous,
        start_p=0, start_q=0,
        test="adf",
        d=pmd.arima.ndiffs(timeseriesarray, max_d=3),
        max_order=15,
        trace=trace)
